RAPPERS Kwesta and Crazy J &ldquo;stole my beat&rdquo;!These are the words of an up-and-coming rapper Busang Ramasehla, aka &ldquo;Mac Murphy&rdquo;.Mac (22) claimed the beat used for the track No Lie was stolen from him by Crazy J&rsquo;s producer, known only as Sphiwe.He said his track is titled Lutho and he&rsquo;s been performing it at various events around Daveyton.&ldquo;I did all the work at Solo Studios where I met Sphiwe,&rdquo; said Mac.&ldquo;I left the beat and the vocals with him. I never thought he&rsquo;d do this. I still have the raw files. It&rsquo;s my beat,&rdquo; Mac said.&ldquo;I knew he was working with Crazy J &ndash; and that Crazy J was the one funding his music career. According to Mac he was hurt by someone he trusted. Sphiwe said: I use to work with Mac and taught him some of the things when it comes to production. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a producer and this year I got a record label. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s when Mac started acting up.&rdquo;Sphiwe believes his success turned his friends against him. &ldquo;It started when they heard I was working with Kwesta. &ldquo;They started calling me a cheese boy. &ldquo;Yes, I&rsquo;ve worked with Mac, but the one Crazy J and Kwesta are using is not his,&rdquo; Sphiwe said.Kwesta said he went to the studio and recorded the track. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know who got the beat from who. &ldquo;I agreed to work with them, that&rsquo;s it,&rdquo; he said.Crazy J said: &ldquo;Sphiwe said he thinks people are jealous that he&rsquo;s working with me. &ldquo;He showed me the data of the beat on the computer he used for it, so I don&rsquo;t know how that&rsquo;s possible.&rdquo;